    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"a04s5-md02\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"### Task 5.2 — Choose the reference SSP-RCP scenario\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"The MOEA evaluates each candidate policy under a **reference scenario**. \\\\\\n\",\n",
    "    \"JUSTICE supports eight SSP-RCP pathways (indices 0–7).\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Question:** Which scenario(s) should the reference optimisation use, and why?\\n\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"code\",\n",
    "   \"execution_count\": null,\n",
    "   \"id\": \"a04s5-c02\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {\n",
    "    \"execution\": {\n",
    "     \"iopub.execute_input\": \"2026-04-02T11:14:11.274430Z\",\n",
    "     \"iopub.status.busy\": \"2026-04-02T11:14:11.274380Z\",\n",
    "     \"iopub.status.idle\": \"2026-04-02T11:14:11.276546Z\",\n",
    "     \"shell.execute_reply\": \"2026-04-02T11:14:11.276118Z\"\n",
    "    }\n",
    "   },\n",
    "   \"outputs\": [],\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"# YOUR ANSWER HERE:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# SSP-RCP scenarios supported by JUSTICE \\n\",\n",
    "    \"# Source: justice/util/enumerations.py — Scenario class\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# Hint: from justice.util.enumerations import Scenario; [print(s.value[0], s.value[3]) for s in Scenario]\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"id\": \"a04s5-md03\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"### Task 5.3 — Select FaIR climate ensemble members\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"JUSTICE runs with 1001 FaIR ensemble members.  The 1001 ensemble members represent uncertainty about how the physical climate system responds to CO₂. Each member is a different configuration of climate parameters, most importantly equilibrium climate sensitivity (ECS), which is how much global temperature rises when CO₂ doubles.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Nobody knows the exact value of ECS. Scientists estimate it's somewhere between ~2.5°C and ~4°C, but there's quite a bit of uncertainty. Rather than picking one value and pretending it's correct, FaIR runs 1001 plausible versions of the climate system simultaneously.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"So when JUSTICE outputs fraction_above_threshold:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"if a policy where to run through all 1001 climate versions, it\\n\",\n",
    "    \"counts how many of them exceed 2°C\\n\",\n",
    "    \"reports that fraction (e.g. 0.4 means 400 out of 1001 members crossed 2°C)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"You can imagine that the same emission policy can lead to different temperature outcomes depending on which version of the climate turns out to be correct.\\\\\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Using all 1001 members per function evaluation is accurate but makes a 50 000-NFE run \\\\\\n\",\n",
    "    \"take weeks on a laptop. So you need to make a well-justified pragmatic choice.  You are\\\\\\n\",\n",
    "    \"of course welcome to explore DelftBlue HPC to do the run across the entire ECS ensemble. \\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Important:** FaIR ensemble indices are **not ordered by ECS** — index 5 is not \\\\\\n\",\n",
    "    \"necessarily warmer than index 4. The indices are identifiers, not a ranking.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**How to pass ensemble members to JUSTICE:**\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"climate_ensembles accepts either a single integer or a list of integers:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"```python\\n\",\n",
    "    \"JUSTICE(climate_ensembles=[0, 250, 500, 750, 1000])                   # hand-picked subset\\n\",\n",
    "    \"JUSTICE(climate_ensembles=list(np.linspace(0, 1000, 10, dtype=int)))  # evenly-spaced subset of 10\\n\",\n",
    "    \"JUSTICE(climate_ensembles= ensemble_indices)  # the ensemble_indices will be defined by you below. \\n\",\n",
    "    \"```\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Question:** How many ensemble members should a local optimisation run use, and how \\\\\\n\",\n",
    "    \"should they be selected?\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"> The full 1001-member would be very doable for HPC runs, check out: https://www.tudelft.nl/dhpc/system.\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
