    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"### Task 5.4 — Define the objectives and ε-resolution\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"JUSTICE returns four scalar outputs per policy evaluation. You must decide:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- Which to include as **optimisation objectives**\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- The **direction** (minimise or maximise)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"- The **ε value** — the Pareto archive resolution; smaller ε = finer front \\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"The four outputs and their typical scales are:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| Output | Typical scale | Meaning |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"|---|---|---|\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `welfare` | ~10²–10⁵ | Absolute welfare loss (Utilitarian aggregation) |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `fraction_above_threshold` | 0 – 1 | Fraction of FaIR members where global T > 2°C in 2100 |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `welfare_loss_damage` | ~10³–10⁴ | Welfare burden attributable to climate damages |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"| `welfare_loss_abatement` | ~10³–10⁴ | Welfare burden attributable to abatement costs |\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"**Question:** What direction should each objective have and what ε-value is appropriate?\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Tips:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"> All four objectives are physically *lower-is-better*. However, the JUSTICE model computes `welfare_loss_damage` and `welfare_loss_abatement` as **positive magnitudes** (`np.abs()` of the welfare function output). This may seem counterintuitive: The welfare function applied to small positive costs returns a large negative number, so np.abs is inversely related to actual cost — larger = less damage)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"> ε should be proportional to the objective's scale: 0.1 and 0.25 give fine resolution over the 0–1 ranges; 10.0 gives ~0.1–1% resolution over the 10³–10⁴ welfare loss range.\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
